  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 889faa658c7b2c94ea4fff939bf8022e, type: 3}
  m_Name: DialogNPCInfirmary
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  Name: Stefano
  Icon: {fileID: -2105629146, guid: d556a7f542c7d03429c5a535ce31a084, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 1
  Greeting: Will 11Labs
  Day1Dialog:
  - 'I was sent from the hospital in Birgu because they believed I could help here.

    I
    believed it too. Back there, wounds arrived in order, with space for names, for
    records, for prayer.

    Here, everything comes at once. I still tell myself
    this is just another ward, only closer to the walls.

    By tomorrow, I suspect
    that illusion will not survive.'
  Day2FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'Cannon wounds do not behave like wounds in the books.

    You learn very quickly
    which voices will not be heard again by morning.

    By tomorrow, I fear I will
    recognise that look the moment someone is carried in.'
  Day2MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'Yesterday I still believed I was learning how to save them.

    Today, I caught
    myself looking at a man and knowing he would not see another sunrise before anyone
    said a word.

    I spoke gently to him anyway, but the words felt like a ritual
    I was performing for myself.

    By tomorrow, that kind of knowing will come
    without any effort at all.'
  Day3FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'There are moments now when mercy and cruelty feel dangerously close.

    When
    a man begs you to stop touching his wounds, to stop moving him, to stop trying,
    you realise how small the space is between helping and hurting.

    The training
    in Birgu never prepared me for choosing whether to continue.

    By tomorrow,
    I fear I will stop asking myself if I have done the right thing and only ask
    whether the ordeal has ended.'
  Day3MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'Last night, I prayed for someone to die.

    Not because I wished them harm,
    but because I could not bear to watch their suffering stretch into another hour.

    The
    words felt wrong as I spoke them, but the relief I felt when they passed was
    unmistakable.

    By tomorrow, I am not sure I will still recognise that as
    something I should confess.'
  Day4FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'Since this morning, the wounded have not stopped coming.

    The pattern of
    their injuries tells me someone very skilled now commands the guns: more shattered
    bone, fewer lucky escapes.

    By tomorrow, I will see only the damage and the
    little time left to act, nothing more.'
  Day4MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Today, I treated a man from the other side.\nFor a moment, I waited to feel
    something different\u2014anger, satisfaction, anything\u2014but he screamed the
    same way as the others, and then he went quiet the same way too.\nIt unsettles
    me how little difference there was.\nBy tomorrow, I suspect the uniforms will
    blur, and all that will remain is the sound they make when they realise they
    are not going home."
  Day5FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'You find me on a day when my hands no longer shake.

    Once, I would have
    taken pride in that. Now, it feels like a sign that something essential is being
    worn away.

    I move from body to body, and the faces fade faster than the
    wounds.

    If this continues tomorrow, I fear I will remember only weight,
    heat, and the point at which the breathing stops.'
  Day5MetBeforeDialog:
  - "I no longer pray for guidance.\nI pray that whatever waits beyond these walls
    will not follow me when this is over.\nIf I survive, I do not know how I will
    stand in a quiet room again without hearing these voices.\nBy tomorrow, if there
    is a tomorrow for me, I may not fear anything at all\u2014and that possibility
    frightens me more than the blood on the floor."
  Day1Audio: {fileID: 8300000, guid: c51301f98158dc248bb7d645dcc66285, type: 3}
